WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
I'm Keaton. I'm a solutions developer at KSNR. We're a market research company about 40 years

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000
old and we do database work with a variety of clients across a variety of sectors. I

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.280
feel like this talk is appropriately placed because a lot of the data that we get is from

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:29.600
surveys so I don't have to explain survey data. But I want to talk today a little bit

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:35.400
about some work we've done over the past year and a half to leverage Quarto and some data

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:43.560
wrangling tools to automate reporting. Before I do that though, I want to talk about my

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:50.959
great grandmother's zucchini pickles. Bear with me. So I'm a bit of a foodie and a collector

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:58.840
of recipes. I have a lot of these recipe cards that have been handed down in my family. And

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:07.320
they provide a really nice window into history. But they also have some interesting facets

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:14.120
about them. So the first is that they're kind of hard to read. I don't know about you all.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:20.260
I don't read or write cursive on a regular basis very much anymore. And when I first

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:24.760
looked at this recipe, I actually thought it called for a half a cup of suet instead

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:31.959
of salt. And I think those pickles probably would have turned out a lot differently.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:36.879
You can also see some self-edits here. My great grandmother is correcting her cursive

00:01:36.879 --> 00:01:42.480
or her spelling, which is pretty great and pretty interesting to see. There's also some

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:48.839
ambiguous instructions, right? What is a fairly fine chop? That means different things to

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:57.559
different people. There's retro or hard-to-find components, right? Pickling spice varies by

00:01:57.559 --> 00:02:01.800
region, right? The same spices in one part of the world in pickling spice might be very

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:06.360
different from another. There's some scaling challenges, right? If I wanted to become a

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:11.960
zucchini pickle maven and make thousands of gallons of these, this recipe might not scale

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:17.399
well. And finally, I can't ask for clarification, right? My great grandmother passed away a

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:21.600
number of years ago. I can't call her on the phone and ask her questions about this

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:28.160
recipe. So why am I talking about zucchini pickles? I would argue that reporting and

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:35.279
data pipelines share a lot of similarities with recipes. Often we don't have up-to-date

00:02:35.279 --> 00:02:42.880
or thorough documentation on our pipelines. If those pipelines don't contain mechanisms

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:49.880
for version control are based in GUI-based or graphical user interfaced clicking workflows,

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:57.119
it's hard to see the history and understand those self-edits. Often we're working in orgs

00:02:57.119 --> 00:03:04.000
with outdated toolkits, and there's conversations around, why should I fix this? It isn't broken.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:10.320
Why are we spending time updating things? Scaling challenges, just like scaling up to

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:17.160
that thousand-gallon batch of pickles is often challenging. And sometimes we can't

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:22.360
ask for clarification, right? We have team members that leave or move on, and we can't

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:29.240
ask them specifics about knowledge that only exists in their head. So I want to talk a

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:35.559
little bit about our recipe challenge that we've been working on. So we have survey data

00:03:35.559 --> 00:03:41.520
from a variety of global respondents, folks all over the world, for this particular project.

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:47.199
Our client wanted PDFs that represent the answers for every respondent in the survey.

00:03:47.199 --> 00:03:54.320
So one PDF per respondent. We have hundreds of respondents per wave, and that wave is

00:03:54.320 --> 00:04:00.559
repeated and this project is repeated every year, so we're doing this on a rolling basis.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:04.520
Individual reports when we're in that period where we're collecting data from the surveys

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:09.080
need to be generated and passed to the client on a weekly basis.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:14.839
We had a historic pipeline, but it was built in maybe a bit of a retro toolkit, right?

00:04:14.839 --> 00:04:22.839
So mail merge from Microsoft, not a lot of version control, and hard to sort of understand

00:04:22.839 --> 00:04:27.600
what's going on. That's compounded by the fact that we had a team member leave who had

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.880
that knowledge in his head, and we can't ask him about how the original pipeline was built.

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:39.640
So it's a challenge, but it's also an opportunity to rebuild things from scratch.

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:47.359
At KSNR, we often are confronted with really wide SPSS data, so lots of columns, and so

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:52.399
we need to think a little bit about some cross-functional data structure and naming conventions, so

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:56.559
that when we go from the raw survey data that comes out of our platform, it'll play nice

00:04:56.559 --> 00:05:02.320
eventually with Cordo and the tools that I think a lot of us are familiar with in the

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:03.320
room.

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:07.559
And finally, we really wanted to de-silo this entire pipeline, right? We don't want knowledge

00:05:07.559 --> 00:05:12.959
living in the head of one person. We wanted to build replicable infrastructure on GitHub

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:20.600
hosted internally and thorough documentation throughout, so multiple team members can engage

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:22.720
with the process.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:33.959
Okay. So we have our recipe challenge, right? Let's talk a little bit about the how. I'm

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:39.559
going to take a 30,000-foot view of this, mostly because of time constraints. There

00:05:39.559 --> 00:05:44.160
is a QR code throughout. It'll show up again here in a second, and it'll show up again

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:50.000
at the end, where we have a GitHub repo that has a completely anonymized reproducible example

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.320
for folks who really want to do the deep dive on all the code.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:06:00.000
But it starts with raw survey data, and we need to get to something a little closer to

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.359
more tidy data that we want to work with in our pipeline. This was a people process, right?

00:06:06.359 --> 00:06:11.640
It involved a lot of collaborative effort with our survey programming team and conversations

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:17.679
around why the data needed to be wrangled a bit and a little longer, and eventually

00:06:17.679 --> 00:06:23.720
we settled on a format that worked, and they also helped us build a pipeline where this

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:28.720
is automated to be generated or updated hourly. So we have a flow of data coming through that

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:34.160
we can now put into the pipeline.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:41.239
So this is the pipeline. A lot of components here. On a given run of this, the data, that

00:06:41.239 --> 00:06:47.920
sort of semi-wrangled data, kind of tidy data, gets put into a data store, and that

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:54.279
data store then gets fed into this main automation script. That main automation script ingests

00:06:54.279 --> 00:07:00.720
a lot of other things, so we have some helper functions that do more complete data wrangling

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:07.260
and deal with some other issues, and then we also have a Cordo template and a YAML header,

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:12.059
and those define the basic structure of what the PDF reports should look like, right? And

00:07:12.059 --> 00:07:17.459
we have a template and a YAML header so we can parameterize some of that data, pass it

00:07:17.459 --> 00:07:22.619
through the entire system, and create the individual reports.

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:27.260
Lot of, again, familiar data wrangling tools leveraged throughout, but particularly in

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:37.940
those helper functions. The output of a run via the main automation script is the PDFs

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:45.140
get pushed to the report store, and then finally someone, often me, who is doing these runs,

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:50.019
moves those to our shared network drive at our company, hand it off to the business team

00:07:50.019 --> 00:07:55.380
so they can do QA, QC, and eventually deliver them to the client.

00:07:55.380 --> 00:08:03.459
Okay, 30,000 foot view, some basics on overall how it works, but like most things, there's

00:08:03.459 --> 00:08:09.220
some hurdles, right? Like Julia Child here, confronted with this massive piece of tuna.

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:16.899
How do we cut this up? And I want to talk about two hurdles today. The first is a little

00:08:16.899 --> 00:08:21.179
bit of thought when we were designing this about where we wanted things to sit on the

00:08:21.179 --> 00:08:28.540
automation and flexibility spectrum. The second is we wanted to update the design.

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:32.700
There were a lot of conversations about how far down that road we wanted it to go, if

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:37.059
we wanted to update it at all, and then a little bit about sort of the mechanisms of

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:43.099
changing that formatting. So early in our conversations with project teams, this quote

00:08:43.099 --> 00:08:49.299
came up. They said, we really need it to be automated, but also we need to pick and choose

00:08:49.299 --> 00:08:56.659
which dates we want to run reports for ad hoc, right, at a given time. So to me, that

00:08:56.659 --> 00:09:00.539
doesn't sound a lot like automation. It sounds like we need to be somewhere maybe in the

00:09:00.539 --> 00:09:06.219
middle, right, where we don't have a fully automated solution. It's easier, it's faster.

00:09:06.219 --> 00:09:10.859
Components of it are automated, but we can jump in the places we need to and be flexible

00:09:10.859 --> 00:09:19.780
to get the clients what they need. And there were a couple places where I think this reared

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:25.179
its head. I'm going to focus on one, and that is the story of date ranges. So I'm going

00:09:25.179 --> 00:09:29.580
to show just a little bit of code here. Again, this is straight from the reproducible example

00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:36.539
on GitHub. This is the top of that main automation script. We're reading in the data. Here it's

00:09:36.539 --> 00:09:42.140
a tab-delimited file. We're employing a couple of those custom helper functions, so clean

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:46.419
DF and strip HTML tags to clean up some of the survey text that we're getting from the

00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:51.580
platform. And then we're setting up this filter window. And this is pretty straightforward,

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:56.940
right? We're just saying, like, filter a bunch of data starting at this date and this date,

00:09:56.940 --> 00:10:01.940
pass that forward. But it's a really easy way to get folks across our team who have

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:06.780
more or less experience coding and are a really clear ability to go and run this on

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:14.780
their own. And to that end, we also use functions from the CLI package pretty frequently, providing

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:20.780
some good context in the console, again, thinking about the sort of spectrum of experience that

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:29.659
folks have on our team. On to design. So, again, there were a lot of conversations about

00:10:29.659 --> 00:10:35.140
if we should change the PDF. And if we do want to change it, how should we change it?

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:40.059
And I think we ultimately did decide to make some upgrades. And I think that comes down

00:10:40.059 --> 00:10:45.700
to three reasons. The first is that some minimal upgrades in the formatting and design improved

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:50.099
trust and clarity on the client side. They can see that we're engaged with providing

00:10:50.099 --> 00:10:57.020
great product for them and continually upgrading the experience that they have. That professional

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:01.659
look and upgrades equals more engagement from them, even on something as simple as

00:11:01.659 --> 00:11:07.140
this, where it's really just survey responses. And finally, there were internal impacts.

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:13.460
So, better formatted PDFs allow for faster QA and QC internally and a better overall

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:21.979
experience for our team. So, let's look at the before and after. So, on the left is what

00:11:21.979 --> 00:11:26.900
clients were getting before. Obviously, I've done some modifications to the content here

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:33.659
to anonymize it. And on the right is after. This is not the most beautiful PDF report

00:11:33.659 --> 00:11:38.020
in the world, by any stretch of the imagination. These are small formatting changes, but we

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:42.700
think they've made a real impact. So, we gave things a little bit of space and breathing

00:11:42.700 --> 00:11:48.900
room in appropriate places. We added quality of life improvements, like subsections, right?

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:53.979
You might want to know what sort of portion of the survey and be able to quickly navigate

00:11:53.979 --> 00:12:00.500
to it. We removed all of the boxing in these legacy PDF formatting, and we added some custom

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:07.020
headers and footers. Again, quality of life improvements, pretty basic, but generally

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:14.099
enhancing the design of the PDF. Okay. So, how did we implement all of those formatting

00:12:14.099 --> 00:12:20.619
changes? Well, the answer, and again, this is not to read specifically. If you want to

00:12:20.619 --> 00:12:24.820
dive into all of this code, again, this all comes from the GitHub repo. It's a lot of

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:31.380
LaTeX. I'm not an expert in LaTeX, and it turns out no one at our company is an expert

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:36.580
in LaTeX. So, that makes this portion of the pipeline pretty brittle, right? We're trying

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:41.140
to de-silo it. We're trying to make sure that it's maintainable into the future. And so,

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:47.940
one thing that's on our roadmap is converting this over to types in the next year, I think.

00:12:47.940 --> 00:12:52.140
And that comes out of great talks last year at Paws at Conf about types integration with

00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:56.619
Cordo. That's something we're really excited about to make these formatting changes easier

00:12:56.619 --> 00:13:01.979
to understand and maybe de-silo that a little bit.

00:13:01.979 --> 00:13:09.820
So, take-home story. We saw really big efficiency gains. This is the second time that we've

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:15.580
run this pipeline. I think it finished about a month and a half ago. The project teams

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:21.260
reported that they saw efficiency gains of 50%, which is pretty big. We cut their time

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:25.619
in half in the amount of time that they have to spend generating these reports and interacting

00:13:25.619 --> 00:13:31.340
with it, which is pretty huge. The design improvements, well-received by the client.

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:36.780
We had an opportunity to level up our team skills by migrating away from this mail merge

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:42.700
approach to a modern toolkit with Cordo and the Tidyverse. Consistency was essentially

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:51.659
the same, and errors were the same. And again, part of that is because of the speed of the

00:13:51.659 --> 00:13:57.419
